{"title_page": "Sir Harold Hillier Gardens", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox park\n| name           = \n| image          = File:Hillier Arboretum view.JPG\n| image_size     = \n| image_alt      = \n| image_caption  = An autumn view from the visitor centre\n| map            = Hampshire \n| map_width      = \n| map_caption    = Location in Hampshire\n| type           = [[Arboretum]]\n| location       = \n| nearest_city   = Southampton\n| coordinates    = {{coord|51.0111|N|1.4666|W|region:GB|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| area           = 180 acres\n| created        = 1953\n| operator       = [[Hampshire County Council]]\n| visitation_num = \n| status         = Grade II\n| designation    = \n| open           = \n}}\nThe '''Sir Harold Hillier Gardens''' is an [[arboretum]] comprising 72 hectares (180 acres) accommodating over 42,000 trees and shrubs in about 12,000 [[taxa]], notably a collection of [[oak]]s, [[camellia]], [[magnolia]] and [[rhododendron]].<ref name=\"hill\">[http://www.hilliergardens.org.uk/the-gardens.html www.hilliergardens.org.uk]</ref>\n\nThe Gardens are located {{convert|5|km|0|abbr=on}} northeast of the town of [[Romsey]] in [[Hampshire]], [[England]], and were formerly known simply as the Hillier Arboretum, founded by nurseryman [[Harold Hillier]] in June 1953 when he acquired Jermyn's House and its grounds. \n\nThe arboretum was given to [[Hampshire County Council]] in 1977 to be managed as a charitable trust. Sir Harold Hillier was knighted in 1983, just two years before his death at age 80 in 1985.<ref name=\"hill\"/>\n\nThe Gardens were listed as Grade II on the [[National Register of Historic Parks and Gardens]] in 1997.<ref>{{NHLE|desc=Sir Harold Hillier gardens and arboretum|num= 1001367 |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nRun as a charity the Gardens are continually developed to further Sir Harold\u2019s philosophy of horticulture, conservation, education and recreation. Patrons include: [[Lord Sainsbury of Preston Candover KG]] and [[Roy Lancaster]] CBE VMH who was formerly the first Curator. President: [[HRH The Duchess of Cornwall]]. A dedicated team of 18 experienced [[horticulturalist]] and [[arborists]] look after the collection alongside students and a team of 200 volunteers. \n\n\n== Collection ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=May 2020}}\n[[File:Autumn Colours @ Hillier Gardens (2953706135).jpg|thumb|Autumn Colours]]\nSir Harold Hillier Gardens has one of the largest collections of hardy trees and shrubs in the world and is famous for its collection of rare plants. It is home to 14 [[National Plant Collection]]s including: \n\n* [[Carpinus]] (hornbeam)\n* [[Cercidiphyllum]] (katsura trees)\n* [[Cornus]] (dogwoods)\n* [[Corylus]] (hazels)\n* [[Cotoneaster]]\n* [[Hamamelis]] (witch hazels)\n* Hillier Plants\n* [[Hypericum]] \n* [[Ligustrum]] (privets)\n* [[Lithocarpus]] (stone/tanbark oak)\n* [[Metasequoia]] (dawn redwoods)\n* [[Photinia]]\n* [[Pinus]] (pines)\n* [[Quercus]] (oaks)\n\nSir Harold Hillier Gardens has the most rare collection of [[Champion Trees]] in Britain and Ireland with 611 trees that are considered to be the largest, finest, or most rare of their species, as recorded by the Tree Register of the British Isles in 2020. The collection includes [[Metasequoia glyptostroboides]], from the original batch of seed received by the Arnold Arboretum from China and distributed in 1948, its first introduction to the West. The young shoot is the emblem of the Gardens.\n\n== Gardens ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=May 2020}}\nA variety of landscapes have been designed for seasonal interest all year round.\n\n* '''Winter Garden''' - was opened by [[Lord Heseltine]] in 1998. It was extended in 2014 and now covers over 4 acres, one of the largest Winter Gardens in Europe. It has more than 650 plants grown for their winter beauty. Planting features a palette of bark, bold coloured stems, scent and foliage.\n\n* '''Acer Valley''' - A valley of Japanese and other [[maples]] and shaded by mature oaks.\n\n* '''Bog Garden''' - Here [[Bamboos]] are mixed with bold herbaceous perennials such as the enormous [[Gunnera manicata]]\n\n* '''Centenary Border''' - The longest double mixed border in the country.  Originally planted in 1964 by [[Sir Harold Hillier]] to celebrate the 100th anniversary of the founding of the Winchester nursery by his grandfather. It was planted with alternating 22 yard bays, to reflect Sir Harold's interest in cricket. It was decided in 2010 to develop a more suitable border and infrastructure to open up the border all year round. Centenary Border is now the longest double mixed border in the country and was officially opened by [[HRH Duchess of Cornwall]] in 2013.\n\n* '''Children's Education Garden''' - created for the education programmes provided by the Gardens it includes the Mediterranean, Oak and the \u2018musical\u2019 Bamboo classrooms with exotic plants and herbs. Six dipping ponds filled with aquatic life and dragonflies. An allotment kept for growing vegetables. Open in July 20016 by [[Sir David Attenborough]]\n\n* '''Gurkha Memorial Garden''' - The Gurkha Memorial Garden was created in 1997 with generous funding from the Kadoorie Foundation of Hong Kong. Planted selection of Nepal's unique flora and plants originally collected as seed in Nepal. The chautara here displays the 12 regimental regiments. It is in memory of Sir Horace Kadoories (1902-1995).\n\n*'''The Heather Garden''' - contains a range of heathers, delightful trees and shrubs. This gives all year interest of both flower and foliage.\n \n*'''Himalayan Valley''' - is lined with Azaleas, Rhododendrons, Hydrangeas, Pieris, and many other plants \n \n*'''Hydrangea Walk''' - is planted with a selection of the mophead and lacecap forms of [[Hydrangea macrophylla]]. There are also some [[Hydrangea paniculata]] mixed with a variety of Viburnums.\n \n*'''Magnolia Avenue''' - forms an avenue running from the front of Jermyn's House. Established by Sir Harold, these [[magnolias]] are now fully mature.\n\n*'''Meadows''' - contain [[common spotted orchid]], Dactylorhiza fuchsia, [[yellow rattle]], [[Rhinanthus minor]].\n\n*'''Peony Border''' - has around 70 different varieties of [[peony]]\n\n*'''The Pond''' - the banks of the pond are several trees of [[swamp cypress]] (Taxodium distichum).  \n\n*'''Rhododendron Woodland''' - with approximately 1,307 different types of Rhododendron. Here is planted a champion specimen of [[Quercus rysophylla]], which was grown from seed collected by Sir Harold while in Mexico.\n\n*'''Valley of Fire''' - lined with North American [[Maples]], [[Sweet Gum]] (Liquidambar) and cherry trees. Shrub beds are planted with [[Sumac]] and [[Lindera]]\n \n*'''Wisteria Border''' - has 20 different [[Wisteria]] \n\nSir Harold Hillier Gardens have planted a Hypericum trial. This three year trial was in association with the Royal Horticultural Society. The aim of the trial is to: establish garden worthiness, resolve any naming problems and assess their medicinal properties. The trial includes approximately 65 different types of plants. The [[Hypericum lancasteri]], grown at the Gardens, is named in honour of patron [[Roy Lancaster]].\n\n== Buildings ==\n\n\n*'''Visitor Pavilion''' - was opened in 2003. The elegant single storey complex was designed by [[Hampshire County Council]] Architects, and has won the SCALA award for the best local authority designed building in the UK. The building is a complementary mix of modern and traditional materials. Dedicated to the memory of [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother]] and visited in 2003 by [[HM The Queen]]. The Visitor Pavilion hosts a gallery space, ticket desk, membership desk, restaurant, gift shop and purpose-built education facility.\n\n*'''Jermyn\u2019s House''' - the original house here could have been built in the early 18th century. The land in 1724 was owned by Farmer Jarman. After being used as a smallpox hospital and inoculation centre in the 18th century. It passed through a number of different owners and in 1951 it was auctioned and the Hillier family took up residence in June 1953. The building now houses the administrative offices for the gardens.<ref>{{cite web |title=History of the Gardens |url=https://www.hants.gov.uk/thingstodo/hilliergardens/about/history |website=Hampshire County Council |accessdate=1 May 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.hilliergardens.org.uk/ Hillier Gardens]\n\n[[Category:Arboreta in England]]\n[[Category:Botanical gardens in England]]\n[[Category:Parks and open spaces in Hampshire]]\n\n\n{{hampshire-geo-stub}}\n{{UK-garden-stub}}\n{{arboretum-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox park\n| name           = \n| image          = File:Hillier Arboretum view.JPG\n| image_size     = \n| image_alt      = \n| image_caption  = An autumn view from the visitor centre\n| map            = Hampshire \n| map_width      = \n| map_caption    = Location in Hampshire\n| type           = [[Arboretum]]\n| location       = \n| nearest_city   = Southampton\n| coordinates    = {{coord|51.0111|N|1.4666|W|region:GB|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| area           = 180 acres\n| created        = 1953\n| operator       = [[Hampshire County Council]]\n| visitation_num = \n| status         = Grade II\n| designation    = \n| open           = \n}}\nThe '''Sir Harold Hillier Gardens''' is an [[arboretum]] comprising 72 hectares (180 acres) accommodating over 42,000 trees and shrubs in about 12,000 [[taxa]], notably a collection of [[oak]]s, [[camellia]], [[magnolia]] and [[rhododendron]].<ref name=\"hill\">[http://www.hilliergardens.org.uk/the-gardens.html www.hilliergardens.org.uk]</ref>\n\nThe Gardens are located {{convert|5|km|0|abbr=on}} northeast of the town of [[Romsey]] in [[Hampshire]], [[England]], and were formerly known simply as the Hillier Arboretum, founded by nurseryman [[Harold Hillier]] in June 1953 when he acquired Jermyn's House and its grounds. \n\nThe arboretum was given to [[Hampshire County Council]] in 1977 to be managed as a charitable trust. Sir Harold Hillier was knighted in 1983, just two years before his death at age 80 in 1985.<ref name=\"hill\"/>\n\nThe Gardens were listed as Grade II on the [[National Register of Historic Parks and Gardens]] in 1997.<ref>{{NHLE|desc=Sir Harold Hillier gardens and arboretum|num= 1001367 |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nRun as a charity the Gardens are continually developed to further Sir Harold\u2019s philosophy of horticulture, conservation, education and recreation. Patrons include: [[Lord Sainsbury of Preston Candover KG]] and [[Roy Lancaster]] CBE VMH who was formerly the first Curator. President: [[HRH The Duchess of Cornwall]]. A dedicated team of 18 experienced [[horticulturalist]] and [[arborists]] look after the collection alongside students and a team of 200 volunteers. \n\n\n== Collection ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=May 2020}}\n[[File:Autumn Colours @ Hillier Gardens (2953706135).jpg|thumb|Autumn Colours]]\nSir Harold Hillier Gardens has one of the largest collections of hardy trees and shrubs in the world and is famous for its collection of rare plants. It is home to 14 [[National Plant Collection]]s including: \n\n* [[Carpinus]] (hornbeam)\n* [[Cercidiphyllum]] (katsura trees)\n* [[Cornus]] (dogwoods)\n* [[Corylus]] (hazels)\n* [[Cotoneaster]]\n* [[Hamamelis]] (witch hazels)\n* Hillier Plants\n* [[Hypericum]] \n* [[Ligustrum]] (privets)\n* [[Lithocarpus]] (stone/tanbark oak)\n* [[Metasequoia]] (dawn redwoods)\n* [[Photinia]]\n* [[Pinus]] (pines)\n* [[Quercus]] (oaks)\n\nSir Harold Hillier Gardens has the most rare collection of [[Champion Trees]] in Britain and Ireland with 611 trees that are considered to be the largest, finest, or most rare of their species, as recorded by the Tree Register of the British Isles in 2020. The collection includes [[Metasequoia glyptostroboides]], from the original batch of seed received by the Arnold Arboretum from China and distributed in 1948, its first introduction to the West. The young shoot is the emblem of the Gardens.\n\n== Gardens ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=May 2020}}\nA variety of landscapes have been designed for seasonal interest all year round.\n\n* '''Winter Garden''' - was opened by [[Lord Heseltine]] in 1998. It was extended in 2014 and now covers over 4 acres, one of the largest Winter Gardens in Europe. It has more than 650 plants grown for their winter beauty. Planting features a palette of bark, bold coloured stems, scent and foliage.\n\n* '''Acer Valley''' - A valley of Japanese and other [[maples]] and shaded by mature oaks.\n\n* '''Bog Garden''' - Here [[Bamboos]] are mixed with bold herbaceous perennials such as the enormous [[Gunnera manicata]]\n\n* '''Centenary Border''' - The longest double mixed border in the country.  Originally planted in 1964 by [[Sir Harold Hillier]] to celebrate the 100th anniversary of the founding of the Winchester nursery by his grandfather. It was planted with alternating 22 yard bays, to reflect Sir Harold's interest in cricket. It was decided in 2010 to develop a more suitable border and infrastructure to open up the border all year round. Centenary Border is now the longest double mixed border in the country and was officially opened by [[HRH Duchess of Cornwall]] in 2013.\n\n* '''Children's Education Garden''' - created for the education programmes provided by the Gardens it includes the Mediterranean, Oak and the \u2018musical\u2019 Bamboo classrooms with exotic plants and herbs. Six dipping ponds filled with aquatic life and dragonflies. An allotment kept for growing vegetables. Open in July 20016 by [[Sir David Attenborough]]\n\n* '''Gurkha Memorial Garden''' - The Gurkha Memorial Garden was created in 1997 with generous funding from the Kadoorie Foundation of Hong Kong. Planted selection of Nepal's unique flora and plants originally collected as seed in Nepal. The chautara here displays the 12 regimental regiments. It is in memory of Sir Horace Kadoories (1902-1995).\n\n*'''The Heather Garden''' - contains a range of heathers, delightful trees and shrubs. This gives all year interest of both flower and foliage.\n \n*'''Himalayan Valley''' - is lined with Azaleas, Rhododendrons, Hydrangeas, Pieris, and many other plants \n \n*'''Hydrangea Walk''' - is planted with a selection of the mophead and lacecap forms of [[Hydrangea macrophylla]]. There are also some [[Hydrangea paniculata]] mixed with a variety of Viburnums.\n \n*'''Magnolia Avenue''' - forms an avenue running from the front of Jermyn's House. Established by Sir Harold, these [[magnolias]] are now fully mature.\n\n*'''Meadows''' - contain [[common spotted orchid]], Dactylorhiza fuchsia, [[yellow rattle]], [[Rhinanthus minor]].\n\n*'''Peony Border''' - as around 70 different varieties of [[peony]]\n\n*'''The Pond''' - the banks of the pond are several trees of [[swamp cypress]] (Taxodium distichum).  \n\n*'''Rhododendron Woodland''' - with approximately 1,307 different types of Rhododendron. Here is planted a champion specimen of [[Quercus rysophylla]], which was grown from seed collected by Sir Harold while in Mexico.\n\n*'''Valley of Fire''' - lined with North American [[Maples]], [[Sweet Gum]] (Liquidambar) and cherry trees. Shrub beds are planted with [[Sumac]] and [[Lindera]]\n \n*'''Wisteria Border''' - has 20 different [[Wisteria]] \n\nSir Harold Hillier Gardens have planted a Hypericum trial. This three year trial was in association with the Royal Horticultural Society. The aim of the trial is to: establish garden worthiness, resolve any naming problems and assess their medicinal properties. The trial includes approximately 65 different types of plants. The [[Hypericum lancasteri]], grown at the Gardens, is named in honour of patron [[Roy Lancaster]].\n\n== Buildings ==\n\n\n*'''Visitor Pavilion''' - was opened in 2003. The elegant single storey complex was designed by [[Hampshire County Council]] Architects, and has won the SCALA award for the best local authority designed building in the UK. The building is a complementary mix of modern and traditional materials. Dedicated to the memory of [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother]] and visited in 2003 by [[HM The Queen]]. The Visitor Pavilion hosts a gallery space, ticket desk, membership desk, restaurant, gift shop and purpose-built education facility.\n\n*'''Jermyn\u2019s House''' - the original house here could have been built in the early 18th century. The land in 1724 was owned by Farmer Jarman. After being used as a smallpox hospital and inoculation centre in the 18th century. It passed through a number of different owners and in 1951 it was auctioned and the Hillier family took up residence in June 1953. The building now houses the administrative offices for the gardens.<ref>{{cite web |title=History of the Gardens |url=https://www.hants.gov.uk/thingstodo/hilliergardens/about/history |website=Hampshire County Council |accessdate=1 May 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.hilliergardens.org.uk/ Hillier Gardens]\n\n[[Category:Arboreta in England]]\n[[Category:Botanical gardens in England]]\n[[Category:Parks and open spaces in Hampshire]]\n\n\n{{hampshire-geo-stub}}\n{{UK-garden-stub}}\n{{arboretum-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Murgatroyd49", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGardens:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sir_Harold_Hillier_Gardens"}
